description:
Apostichopus parvimensis is a species of sea cucumber found in the eastern Pacific Ocean. It belongs to the phylum Echinodermata, class Holothuroidea, and the order Aspidochirotida.

Apostichopus parvimensis is a small to medium-sized sea cucumber, typically measuring between 10 to 20 centimeters in length. It has a cylindrical body shape with a rounded anterior and posterior end. The body surface is covered with small, papillae-like projections, which give it a rough, grainy texture.

The species is typically found in shallow to moderate depths, ranging from the intertidal zone to depths of around 100 meters. It prefers rocky or sandy seafloor habitats, where it feeds on detritus and small organic particles suspended in the water column.

Apostichopus parvimensis plays an important role in the marine ecosystem, contributing to the cycling of nutrients and the decomposition of organic matter. It is also a commercially important species, harvested for its edible body wall, which is used in various culinary and medicinal applications.
